# NestJS modular architecture

Apply this structure when creating or changing NestJS API modules in this repo.

## API modules

- Use modular architecture with one primary module per main domain or route.
- Keep each main route behind one primary controller; add secondary controllers only for secondary routes.
- Keep business logic and persistence out of controllers.
- Put input DTOs, output types, and module models in a local `models` folder.
- Validate input DTOs with `class-validator`.
- Prefer simple explicit output types over leaking entities through controllers.
- Put business logic in services.
- Use one service per entity or aggregate when persistence is involved.
- Use MikroORM entities for persistence when adding database-backed models.
- Add an `admin/test` method to each controller as a smoke test endpoint.

## Common module

- Put shared reusable code in `@app/common`.
- Use `@app/common/configs` for global configuration settings.
- Use `@app/common/decorators` for reusable custom decorators.
- Use `@app/common/dtos` for shared DTOs.
- Use `@app/common/guards` for reusable role or permission guards.
- Use `@app/common/interceptors` for shared request or response processing.
- Use `@app/common/notifications` for application-wide notification helpers.
- Use `@app/common/services` for reusable services.
- Use `@app/common/types` for shared TypeScript contracts.
- Use `@app/common/utils` for pure helper functions.
- Use `@app/common/validators` for reusable validation rules.

## Core cross-cutting behavior

- Register global exception filters for consistent API error responses.
- Register global middleware for request-level concerns.
- Use guards for authentication, authorization, roles, and permissions.
- Use interceptors for request processing, response mapping, logging, or timing.
- Keep cross-cutting behavior in core/common infrastructure instead of duplicating it inside feature modules.

## Testing

- Write Jest tests for each controller and service.
- Write e2e tests for each API module.
- Use test doubles for expensive or stateful dependencies.
- Prefer real third-party dependencies only when they are cheap, deterministic, and useful for confidence.
